That's right.  This is a little more syntax at the end, but way less syntax since you don't need to write hundreds of lines of complex stuff in core.h.  Generally speaking, I want there to be a core set of tools in core.h that let anyone easily define any kind of network they want without needing to understand or mess with the implementation details in core.h.  This means core.h needs to have the right primitives that let you define anything else.  I think the tag and skip tools let you do that.  I'm sure there are some things that can be improved, this is still a new dlib feature, but it's important that the way people add new layers and/or define new network architectures isn't by editing core.h.  If that's what is required then the DNN API in dlib will have been a failure in my opinion.  That's not to say that we can't improve things in core.h.  But I don't think we need a special concatenation tool in core.h


Also, here is how an inception template could be written in a cleaner way:

```
// Maybe this declaration could be in dlib somewhere since it's something people might want to reuse.
template <template<typename>class B1, template<typename>class B2, template<typename>class B3, typename SUBNET> using inception3 = concat<tag1,tag2,tag3, tag1<B1<skip4< tag2<B2<skip4< tag3<B3<  tag4<SUBNET>>>>>>>>>>;

// Then a user can make inception blocks by defining the sub blocks
template <typename SUBNET> using block1 = relu<con<5,3,3,1,1,SUBNET>>;
template <typename SUBNET> using block2 = relu<con<8,5,3,1,1,SUBNET>>;
template <typename SUBNET> using block3 = relu<con<20,5,3,1,1,SUBNET>>;
// and then defining their inception block
template <typename SUBNET> using incept = inception3<block1,block2,block3,SUBNET>;

// and then the network type is
using net_type = incept<incept<incept<input<matrix<float>>>>>;
```

The only problem with this is that I need to make a mechanism for defining globally unique tags, since in the above if the blocks have tag1 in them for example, the wrong thing will happen.  There are a few ways to deal with that and I'll add something soonish after I think about it a little more.

