Is there another way to distinguish functions? I have the same problem with functions that are enable_if'd based on the template type.

E.g.:
```
    /**
     * Force evaluation of xexpression.
     * @return xarray or xtensor depending on shape type
     * 
     * \code{.cpp}
     * xarray<double> a = {1,2,3,4};
     * auto&& b = xt::eval(a); // b is a reference to a, no copy!
     * auto&& c = xt::eval(a + b); // c is xarray<double>, not an xexpression
     * \endcode
     */
    template <class T>
    inline auto eval(T&& t)
        -> std::enable_if_t<detail::is_container<std::decay_t<T>>::value, T&&>
    {
        return t;
    }

    template <class T, class I = std::decay_t<T>>
    inline auto eval(T&& t)
        -> std::enable_if_t<!detail::is_container<I>::value && detail::is_array<typename I::shape_type>::value, xtensor<typename I::value_type, std::tuple_size<typename I::shape_type>::value>>
    {
        return xtensor<typename I::value_type, std::tuple_size<typename I::shape_type>::value>(std::forward<T>(t));
    }
```

Hi!

You can either place the facts on the machine you're controlling with ansible in the `/etc/ansible/facts.d/` directory. For example:

    fboender @ client $ cat /etc/ansible/facts.d/users.fact
    {
      "users": ["root", "fboender"]
    }

The custom facts will be retrieved by ansible automatically and when you generate the overview, the variables will be placed under the 'Host local facts' section.

You can also create your own hand-crafted ansible facts output directory and put custom and local facts in there. This is done on the ansible control server. For example:

    fboender @ ansible $ cat out_custom/host.example.com
    {
        "custom_facts": {
            "software": {
                "apache": {
                  "version": "2.4",
                  "install_src": "backport_deb"
                }
            }
        },
        "ansible_facts": {
            "ansible_local": {
                "foo": "bar"
            }
        }
    }

This can be combined with the host facts that ansible fetched itself with the "`setup`" module. This requires that you specify two output directories:

    ansible-cmdb -i hosts out/ out_custom/ > cmdb.html

This will place custom_facts under the heading "Custom variables" and the local facts under "Host local facts".

