@tagliala I may be mistaken but on some screen reader / browser combinations having both a title and aria-label can result in both of those being read out to a screen reader which might lead to confusion and repeated content for a screen reader user. 

@karlgroves If users are concerned that an icon on its own may require additional context to be displayed via tooltip for additional affordance it may be desirable to create a separate tooltip element that can be triggered on hover of the anchor tag. 

In addition this same tooltip could be triggered on focus of the anchor tag which is an additional usability enhancement for users who may be using keyboard navigation and therefore wouldn't be able to see the title tooltip displayed on mouse hover, which may be a concern for users with motor disabilities. (my untested assumption here is that a title attribute only displays on hover of the element is attributed to and not on focus).

If people do decide to create an external tooltip to provide this extra information it would probably be best to hide this element from a screen reader via aria-hidden=true as they would be provided the same information via the aria-label attribute assuming the tooltip contains the same value as the aria-label. (Alternatively if this tooltip is used to create descriptive information over an above the name of the icon/action alone the aria-describedby property could be used if the tooltip contains information about the purpose of the anchor tag).

